ative art expresses the artistic zeal of craftsmen in Kashmir. The origin of this art goes back to when accomplished artists were invited from Central Asia by King Zain-ul-Abidin. Highly favoured by Mughal Emperors of 15th and 16th Century, the art of handmade paper received a revolutionary fillip and provided a new area for craftsmanship. This craft opened doors and gave variety to the connoisseurs who till then used to admire the workmanship of wood workers and painters.\r\n\r\nOriginally known in Kashmir as Kar-i-qalamdan or Kar-i-munaqqash, papier mâché was limited to creating delicate work of art on boxes and layers of polished paper. With the advent of the Mughal Raj this art form reached endless possibilities where they were integrated in creating palanquins, ceilings, windows, doors, and many other such architectural structures. From the palanquins of courtiers to embellishments on woodwork this style of craft was made and handcrafted in Kashmir.\r\n\r\nMadin Sahib Mosque (established in 1444 AD), at the Mughal gardens, at Shalimar in Srinagar and the ceiling at the Shah Hamdan Mosque at Fatehkadal are some such prominent historic places where you can catch a glimpse of this incredible craft form.\r\n\r\nIn Europe this style of art has been famous since 16th century as a low cost alternative to plaster or wood in architecture. It is funny how less we know about history, so next time you visit a heritage building in Europe, keep a look out for paper panels. But, beware you might be disappointed since it is next to impossible to differentiate between them and the wooden panels.\r\n\r\nAlthough this style originated in China, but France was one of the first cities in Europe to absorb this craft style, and the term Papier mâché, which literally means chewed paper is believed to have got its name from French workers in London papier mâché shops who did just that! Well whether it is fact or a myth is difficult to prove now, but at that time went quite viral among 