 ceiling at the Shah Hamdan Mosque at Fatehkadal are some such prominent historic places where you can catch a glimpse of this incredible craft form.\r\n\r\nIn Europe this style of art has been famous since 16th century as a low cost alternative to plaster or wood in architecture. It is funny how less we know about history, so next time you visit a heritage building in Europe, keep a look out for paper panels. But, beware you might be disappointed since it is next to impossible to differentiate between them and the wooden panels.\r\n\r\nAlthough this style originated in China, but France was one of the first cities in Europe to absorb this craft style, and the term Papier mâché, which literally means chewed paper is believed to have got its name from French workers in London papier mâché shops who did just that! Well whether it is fact or a myth is difficult to prove now, but at that time went quite viral among the crowds and was a great way to safeguard their secret recipes and true methods.\r\n\r\nIn China craftsman used this interesting style of art to create helmets which were toughened with several layers of lacquer. Whereas in Egypt there were used to create masks for the dead. Made with paper strips glued in heat or with paper boiled in water and glue, both these forms are finished with reinforcements in form of wire, balloons or textile.\r\n\r\nWith that we come to our papier mâché collections, which include this stunning key holder diligently handcrafted by skilled artisans from using various traditional techniques is great gift during festivals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.kraftstory.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/2.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-129 size-full aligncenter\" src=\"https://www.kraftstory.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/2.jpg\" alt=\"Papier-mâché craft \" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.kraftstory.com/ecraftindia-kundun-lord-ganesha-key-holder\">Shop Now</a>\r\n\r\nShaped as a fan, comes a